This article meticulously details the [timeline](/Timeline) of events that shaped the history of [computing hardware](/Computer_hardware) and software, tracing its origins from the distant past right up to the year 1949. For a broader understanding of the overarching narrative and the evolutionary arc of computing, one should consult the more comprehensive [History of computing](/History_of_computing).

### [History of computing](/History_of_computing)

This section serves as a foundational overview, guiding the reader through the intricate tapestry of computing's evolution. It’s the grand narrative, the one that sets the stage for the more granular details found elsewhere.

#### [Hardware](/Computer_hardware)

The physical embodiment of computation, the hardware, has undergone transformations so profound they’re almost unrecognizable from its nascent stages.

*   [Hardware 1960s to present](/History_of_computing_hardware_(1960s%E2%80%93present)): A deep dive into the more recent, and arguably more explosive, period of hardware development. This is where silicon began to truly dominate.

#### [Software](/Software)

The intangible soul of computing, the instructions that breathe life into the silicon.

*   [Software](/History_of_software): The fundamental principles and early evolution of software.
*   [Software configuration management](/History_of_software_configuration_management): How we started managing the complexity of software development.
*   [Unix](/History_of_Unix): A pivotal operating system that shaped much of modern computing.
*   [Free and open-source software](/History_of_free_and_open-source_software): The philosophical and practical movement that democratized software.

#### [Computer science](/Computer_science)

The theoretical underpinnings and the intellectual discipline that drives innovation.

*   [Artificial intelligence](/History_of_artificial_intelligence): The long, often frustrating, quest to imbue machines with intelligence.
*   [Compiler construction](/History_of_compiler_construction): The art and science of translating human-readable code into machine instructions.
*   [Early computer science](/History_of_computer_science): The foundational concepts that emerged before the digital age truly dawned.
*   [Operating systems](/History_of_operating_systems): The software that manages the hardware, making it usable.
*   [Programming languages](/History_of_programming_languages): The diverse tools developed for communicating with machines.
*   [Prominent pioneers](/List_of_pioneers_in_computer_science): A roll call of the brilliant minds who dared to dream of computation.
*   [Software engineering](/History_of_software_engineering): The discipline of building reliable and maintainable software.

#### Modern concepts

The innovations that have fundamentally reshaped our interaction with technology.

*   [General-purpose CPUs](/History_of_general-purpose_CPUs): The central processing unit, the brain of most modern computers.
*   [Graphical user interface](/History_of_the_graphical_user_interface): The visual revolution that made computers accessible to the masses.
*   [Internet](/History_of_the_Internet): The global network that connected the world.
*   [Laptops](/History_of_laptops): The portable revolution.
*   [Personal computers](/History_of_personal_computers): Bringing computing power to the individual.
*   [Video games](/History_of_video_games): Entertainment and a driving force in technological advancement.
*   [World Wide Web](/History_of_the_World_Wide_Web): The interconnected system of documents and resources.
*   [Cloud](/History_of_cloud_computing): Computing as a utility.
*   [Quantum](/Timeline_of_quantum_computing_and_communication): The next frontier, harnessing the bizarre laws of quantum mechanics.

